Anonymous Sat 30 Apr 2022 13:32:20 No.47338625 Report

>>47332118
I like sci fi. Stranded traveler(s) is a solid theme if you take care. Don't do "super" anything. Humans, anthros, AI, tech, etc. Try to keep it normal. Super powers suck a lot of the fun out of stories. There's enough to work with exchanging ideas between cultures and tech levels without going superpowers. Maybe your humans have been genetically enhanced a bit from what we have in our world, but use a light hand there. Focus on creative and well thought-out plot.

If they are antagonists, it doesn't have to be just two. Could be two groups, but keep focus on particular individuals. Maybe one or two get separated and spend a lot of time alone/among alien anthros. Keep in mind, an entire world is just really, really big. Two people on opposite sides coming into conflict in their (remaining) lifetimes beats some staggering odds.

There is a rare but top quality adventure sci fi book tat is basically your theme, called The World is Round by Tony Rothman. Try to find a copy. It's very impressive for its scope & depth. Like, *REALLY* impressive. It's humanoids landing on a planet with alien humanoids, but change that over to anthros and you can lift a lot of the conceptual framework and turn it into something new.

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tony_Rothman

Interesting twist ..? Something like a large ship of alien anthros experiences a catastrophe. Several lifeboats crashland all over a world inhabited by Iron Age humans beginning to move into a tech/industrial Renaissance. Different landing craft have survivors with different backgrounds & educations, different tech in their escape craft survive, making each landing site a unique micro-culture/tech seed. Which eventually clash, as expressed through local human populations contaminated by them. How do the uncontaminated humans compete & fare?

Anonymous Sat 30 Apr 2022 16:45:11 No.47342087 Report
Quoted By:
>>47341720
I think mysteries are a hard sell here because the relationship almost has to turn into a b-plot.
The external conflict provides enough reason to separate them or cause fights between them. If a writer takes the easy way out and doesn't raise the stakes enough, the romance arc goes nowhere. It's all about what changes the A-plot forces on the b-plot.

So anyone that wants to use the term slowburn in here, that's always what I have in mind. The relationship is the reader's reward.
Now how much of the A-plot you have versus the b-plot is up to the writer. If you have truly interesting characters, the mystery can support itself and have the reader anticipating what will happen during the next b-plot scene.
